            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "Detailed information about your HVAC system's behavior helps technicians diagnose problems more quickly and accurately. Write down or photograph specific issues including: when problems occur (time of day, weather conditions, how long system has been running), what symptoms you observe (weak airflow, insufficient cooling/heating, unusual sounds, odd smells, ice buildup, water leaks), how long problems have persisted (days, weeks, months, getting worse over time), and any patterns you've noticed (happens every afternoon, occurs after monsoon storms, worse in certain rooms). For intermittent problems that come and go, note the frequency and circumstances when issues appear. Picture Rocks' extreme temperature swings and dust conditions create specific failure patterns—documenting when your system struggles most (peak 110+ degree afternoons vs. mild 95-degree mornings) provides valuable diagnostic information. If you've noticed increasing energy bills without explanation, gather 6-12 months of utility statements showing the cost trend. Take photos or videos of visible problems like ice on refrigerant lines, water pooling around indoor units, dust accumulation on outdoor coils, or any physical damage to equipment. This documentation ensures technicians understand your concerns completely even if symptoms aren't actively occurring during the service visit."
